Arrival Delay Prediction¶

Priya Rangarajan

The notebook includes code to Visualize, Prepare and Model data on flights in the first quarter of 2018 in United States for Destination airports ORD and ATL. Various stages of Predictive Modeling from Data Visualization and Preparation to Feature Engineering and Model Training and Evaluation have been implemented to predict arrival delays for flights.¶

Table of Contents:¶

  1. EDA
    Import Libraries and Read Data
    Exploring Delays and Cause of Delays

  2. Data Cleaning, Preparation and Feature Engineering
    Check and Remove Missing Data
    Add Day of Week and Month
    Create Arrival and Departure Bins
    Create Binary Target Variable
    Correlation check and Outliers
    One Hot Encoding

  3. Modeling
    Train Test Split
    Sampling Class Imbalance
    Logistic Regression
    Random Forest Classifier
    Stochastic Gradient Classifier
    Decision Tree Classifier
    Gradient Boost Classifier
    ROC Curve and Model Performance Comparison
    Grid Search and Fine Tuning
    Model Evaluation on Test Data

Create Bins for Arrival and Departure Times ¶

In [60]:
def create_time_bins(time):
    if time < '0359':
       return "LateNight"
    elif time < '0659':
        return "EarlyMorning"
    elif time < '1159':
        return "Morning"
    elif time < '1559':
        return "Afternoon"
    elif time < '2259':
        return "Evening"
    else:
        return "LateNight"

Create Binary Target Variable ¶

In [63]:
def create_target(target):
    if target <= 0.0:
       return 0
    else:
        return 1

Create Target variable for Binary Classification 0 - Not Delayed(Positive Class) ; 1 - Delayed(Negative Class)

Sampling Target Variable to remove Class Imbalance ¶

In [94]:
X['Arr_Target'].value_counts()
Delayed = X[X.Arr_Target == 1]
Not_Delayed = X[X.Arr_Target ==0]
from sklearn.utils import resample
upsampled = resample(Delayed,
                          replace=True, # sample with replacement
                          n_samples=len(Not_Delayed), # match number in majority class
                          random_state=27) 
sampled = pd.concat([Not_Delayed, upsampled])
In [95]:
y_train = sampled.Arr_Target
x_train= sampled.drop('Arr_Target', axis=1)

Data has class imbalance. So we oversample the underrepresented class

In [96]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score,accuracy_score,precision_score,recall_score,f1_score
def cal_spec(y_actual,y_pred,thresh):
    return sum((y_pred < thresh) & (y_actual == 0)) / sum(y_actual == 0)

def print_rep(y_actual,y_pred,thresh):
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_actual,y_pred)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_actual,(y_pred > thresh))
    recall = recall_score(y_actual,(y_pred > thresh))
    precision = precision_score(y_actual,(y_pred > thresh))
    specificity = cal_spec(y_actual,y_pred,thresh)
    f1score = f1_score(y_actual,y_pred)
    print('AUC:%.3f'%auc)
    print('Accuracy:%.3f'%accuracy)
    print('Recall:%.3f'%recall)
    print('Specificity:%.3f'%specificity)
    print('Precision:%.3f'%precision)
    print('f1Score:%.3f'%f1score)
    print('')
    return auc,accuracy,recall,precision,specificity,f1score

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
def plot_roc_curve(fpr,tpr,label = None):
    plt.plot(fpr,tpr,linewidth =2,label=label)
    plt.plot([0,1],[0,1],'k--')
    plt.axis([0,1,0,1])
    plt.xlabel('FPR')
    plt.ylabel('TPR')
